result.execSummary:
The defendant Darus T. Stabler was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Hit and Run, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.67(1).
  • Cause Injury/Operate While und.Influence, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(2).
  • 2nd-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Sebion and Lisa Hirschman appeared by telephone. Victim notification complied with.   Defendant plead no contest to Counts 1, 4 & 7 in 14CF185.  All other counts, plus 14CM242, 15CF4, 14TR4085, 14TR4086 and 14TR4087 to be dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Attorney Hirschman appeared briefly.  Her case is dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Defendant agreed that Attorney Hirschman can be excused from the hearing.  Court recited the charge and possible penalties of the count he is pleading to.    He understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  Felony warnings given.  Defendant understood.  Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty as plead to.  PSI ordered.  Due March 18, 2016.   Sentencing set for 4/4/16 at 10:00 am.  Bond continued.
